		   <tr><td valign="top" class="mform2" ><span class="fs8"><span class="notbold">By: </span><a href="/db/poster.html?user=562509"><span class="">Honimek</span></a><b><span class=""></span></b><br />32 posts
		   <br /><span class="nobr"><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Decent  </span><br />
<br/><a href="/db/classes.html?class=7;mid=1126207258111315696;page=1;howmany=50#1126207258111315696"><img alt="" title="Use this to create a link to this post" src="/shared/garrowrt.png" border="0" height="9" width="11" /> Link to this post</a>

<br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1" alt=""/></span></td>
<td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%">
<p>If your becoming a cleric because you don't want to be bored you realy need to like grouping and playing a support role.  Yes, clerics can solo at low levels.  There is not much differance betwwen a level 10 cleric and a level 10 warrior.  With your buffs in place and your ability to heal yourself you have beter AC and HP.  When the melee classes start using two hand fighting you will start to full behind as a tank.  Focus your equipment on wisdom, carry a shield (bash), and try to stay as proficent at melee as possible.  Since you will be grouping a lot, try to be the leader when ever possible.  Spend leader points on mana regen and NPC health ID.  The newbie armor has been upgraded and is worth questing for now.  Choose Karana as your deity in order to make raising your smithing skills less expensive (steel arrow heads).  There will be times when all you can do is sit, heal, sit heal, which can get boring but sometime thats what you have to do to keep the group alive.  One last thing, place your spells next to your group window so you can switch target and heal quicker.  Good luck</p>
</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td class="fs8"></td></tr></table></td></tr></table>
